event_investment_decisions.event_description:
In the upcoming MLB game, scheduled for September 17 at 7:40PM ET:
If the Los Angeles Angels win, the market will resolve to “Angels”.
If the Milwaukee Brewers win, the market will resolve to “Brewers”.
If the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.
If the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.
To know when a postponed game will be played, please check the home team's schedule on MLB.com for the listed team and look for the game described as a makeup game.

decision.rationale: The Brewers defeated the Angels 9-2. The market correctly priced the Angels at 0.0355, reflecting their very low chance of winning. No mispricing detected, so no bet.
The Brewers won by 7 runs, easily covering the -1.5 spread. The market priced this at 0.85, which seems reasonable given the large margin of victory. No significant mispricing detected, so no bet.
The total runs scored were 11 (9+2), which is over 7.5. The market priced 'Over' at 0.82, which seems reasonable. No significant mispricing detected, so no bet.

decision.rationale: Based on the game recap mentioning a 'five-run outburst in the second inning,' it's highly likely there were no runs in the first inning. The market priced 'Yes' at 0.9955, which seems reasonable. No significant mispricing detected, so no bet.

event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in only a 7.35% probability of a 50+ bps cut in October. While the recent dissenting vote from Governor Miran (who preferred a 50 bps cut) suggests some possibility of a larger cut, the Fed's median projection and market consensus still points toward 25 bps cuts. The low price seems reasonable given the consensus view, but there's a small chance of a larger cut. I'm placing a small bet against this outcome.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 50+ bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in a 78.5% probability of a 25 bps cut in October. Given that the Fed just cut rates and signaled two more cuts for 2025, with market expectations around 70-80% for October, this seems reasonably priced. However, the price has increased significantly recently (from ~0.68 to 0.785), possibly overestimating the probability. I'll place a small bet against this outcome.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in only a 14.5% probability of no change in October. Given the Fed's recent action and clear guidance signaling more cuts, this seems correctly priced. With Fed projections showing two more cuts for 2025 and market expectations around 70-80% for October, the low probability of no change seems appropriate. I won't bet on this market.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: No change in Fed interest rates after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in only a 0.75% probability of a rate increase in October. Given the current economic conditions, Fed guidance, and market expectations, this seems correctly priced. With inflation trending down and labor market showing weakness, a rate increase is highly unlikely. I won't bet on this market.
